TY  - JOUR
AU  - Jehiel, Philippe
AU  - Scotchmer, Suzanne
T1  - Constitutional Rules of Exclusion in Jurisdiction Formation
PY  - 2001
Y1  - 2001/04/01
DO  - 10.1111/1467-937X.00174
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 68
IS  - 2
SP  - 393
EP  - 413
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - The rules under which jurisdictions (nations, provinces) can deny immigration or expel residents are generally governed by a constitution, but there do not exist either positive or normative analyses to suggest what types of exclusion rules are best. We stylize this problem by suggesting four constitutional rules of admission: free mobility, admission by majority vote, admission by unanimous consent, admission by a demand threshold for public goods. In a simple model we characterize the equilibria that result from these rules, and provide a positive theory for which constitutional rules will be chosen.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1467-937X.00174
ER  - 



